<a name="newsitem967580698,64785,"></a> <SPAN CLASS="newstitle">Gordon Infobits</SPAN>
<br>
 
<SPAN CLASS="newsreporter">- <a href="mailto:aurum@vaultnetwork.com" class="newsreporter"><b>Aurum</b></a> @ 1:24 PM PDT </SPAN>
<br>

<SPAN CLASS="newstext">
Gordon kept busy this afternoon with several new posts to the Gameplay Board:<UL><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008933.html"><b>FD & /Quiting Out?</b></a><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: "FD will work 25% of the time on wanderers, 90% of the time when the creatures return to their post."]</i></font> <br><br>All creatures forget about a successfully feigned character once the creature returns to it's spawn point. That of course doesn't apply to creatures that don't have a static spawn. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: Monks hate having to do it, and would prefer that FD worked the old way so that we could use our skill without endangering other adventurers in dungeons. This "cheat", as you call it, is your friendly neighborhood monk's attempt at being as little an inconvenience to you as possible. Don't give them a bad time about it.]</i></font> <br><br>It has been suggested that make anyone feigned automatically "stand up" upon a /q, however we don't have any plans to implement that in the foreseeable future.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008967.html"><b>EverQuest Isn't for Everyone</b></a><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post:  As a casual gamer I don't have hours and hours to sit and play. Unfortunately to get anywhere in this game that's what is REQUIRED.]</i></font> <br><br>It's only "required" because you perceive the need to attain the same levels and equipment as the guy who plays 12 hours per day, even though you only have that many hours per week to play yourself. There are many players of this same type, one which I refer to as the "time-starved powergamer", rather than the "casual gamer". <br><br>The time-starved powergamer holds the same desires and drives as the powergamer, but only has limited time to play due to real-life concerns. The player is driven by advancement and acquisition, whereas the casual gamer is more interested in the gaming experience. <br><br>Would it make sense for us to create a game based around the 10 hours per week figure when the average player plays around 23? The game is set up around that average figure, and someone playing that average amount of time can expect to progress at an average rate. The consequence of this is that people who play double or triple that progress much faster, and people who play half that often want to progress as fast, on a calander basis, as those who play double or triple the average. <br><br>Regardless the advancement or acquisition rate in game, there will always be people who play less than the average. It wouldn't make sense for us to gear the game so that people who play less than average progress at fastest rate. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: As for racing to 60, well you assigned us levels and when you set a cap you set a goal. Everyone wants to achieve that goal although the vast majority never will. 50 was attainable but 60? It's a pipe dream for most and probably the number one reason people will quit EQ because they simply accept the fact it is beyond reach.]</i></font> <br><br>We never expected every play to reach level 50, and certainly never expect everyone to reach level 60 either. The "average" player will reach "average" levels and will never "max out". The important thing is that those levels are there for the people who decide to advance to that point and have the time to do so. I see from your post that your character is level 39 now. That's a very respectable level for someone who can only play a few hours per week. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: Make it so we each have an equal chance to achieve all that is achievable in the game with the exclusion of Veeshan's Peak. Make that dungeon so tough that 200 of your best powergamers can never make it 100 yards into it. That should keep them occupied for a while.]</i></font> <br><br>Games of this nature have to service a broad range of different player types. Sometimes servicing one type of player molds the game in a direction that isn't liked by another type. This will always be the case. Your post seems to suggest that you think that every gamer, regardless of how much time they put in, should be able to go everywhere and do everything. Would it make sense for us to make a game geared with 10 hours per week as an average? Or what of a game geared to 5 hours per week on average? To do what you suggest, that being allowing the 10 hours per week player to advance and acquire at the same rate as is enjoyed by the current 40 hour per week player, we'd have to set the average to about 2 hours per week. What fun would the game be for the average player then? <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: EQ should allow everyone the same opportunity to achieve the same items and experience ]</i></font><br><br>Opportunity is a constant. Everyone in game has the same opportunity. They then decide how much of that opportunity they wish to pursue, guided by personal desires and real-life factors. The variable here is the time that you have to play, and it is that you do not have. <br><br>I do not think that it is fair to say that EQ does not support the casual gamer. It would be fair to say that someone who has more time to play EQ can advance and acquire at a faster rate. However, is there anything really wrong with that?<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/009074.html"><b>Discussion of the Week: Continued</b></a><br>I'm impressed with the number of well thought-out discussions taking place in regards to this topic. As many of you have noticed, the size of the original thread has reached the point where it needs to be closed. I still have to go through it and replies to this one as well to compose some comments, which I'll do later today. Until then, here's the continuation of the thread.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008894.html"><b>Weapon Nerfs</b></a><br>Sevrus_MT, <br><br>My initial post on the subject announcing the plans in regards to these weapons said: <br><br>"While we have no problem with weapons of this delay, they should not have been placed as loot on anything other than deity or dragon level encounters." <br><br>The weapon quoted is indeed on such an encounter.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008845.html"><b>20 Questions</b></a><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 1. Camping. Why couldn't the "long portion" of the camp be put at the OTHER end of the camp? Perhaps the NPC needs time to "craft" the quest item and changes in some way to show that they are ready to give the reward. Let the other items spawn almost continuously, and people would NEED to camp anything but the reward PC. ]</i></font><br><br>It's a doable idea, but wouldn't this be just a camp by another name? Whether I'm camping a creature that I want to kill, or one I want to talk to, it's still a camp. In this case, I can see 20 people standing around an NPC waiting for him to "be ready" and fighting over who can hand him the items fastest. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 2. Are there currently any suits of armor that give some "hidden" effect or bonus by virtue of wearing the entire suit? ]</i></font><br><br>No, there are not. It's a good idea though that might have some application for later implementation or future products. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 3. Are there currently any weapons in the game that have any "hidden" effect? ]</i></font><br><br>Not really. What an item can do is expressly stated upon it. We do have some plans for more cursed weaponry in the future, of course we just might have to be creative to "hide" the effect of the curse. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 4. If the answer to 2 and/or 3 is "no", are there any plans to add this feature to the game? ]</i></font><br><br>See above. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 5. You once said that GZ was going to conduct some tests with the wizard's spells vs. the other caster classes. Have these been completed? ]</i></font><br><br>Actually I believe that Brad said that, and it is indeed our opinion that offensive power is appropriate for the class. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 6. Why, exactly, was the definition of the wizard class changed on the everquest.com page under the classes section? ]</i></font><br><br>What change and when was it made? To my knowledge, it has read what it reads now since release. I believe that there was a change at one time in the beta period where it was changed from "damage" to "magical damage", but that's all I believe happened. Was there something else? <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 7. Are there any plans to introduce items that directly influence/enhance trade skills? (Gnomish Jeweler's Loupe, Dwarven Smith's Hammer, Elven Sewing Needle, etc.)]</i></font> <br><br>Do you mean items that allow you to make better items with trades? It's a good idea, but we no firm plans in that direction. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 8. Why, since dwarves in fantasy literature (and even in EQ) are the finest smiths in all the realms, is there no ore in Kaladim? It even has a mine. ]</i></font><br><br>Good question. There's no ore in Kaladim? Hmmm, I'll check into that to see if it was a design or an oversight. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 9. Why can't enchanters be given a high-level illusion that allows them to change into the nearest ANIMATE object? ]</i></font><br><br>Races are a component of faction, and you adopt whatever race-faction you emulate. There's a lot of special case-coding to handle the animate races that players currently emulate. Opening that up to nearly everything else would be extremely problematic, if not impossible. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 10. Are there any plans to introduce a spell or item that absorbs magic directed at the wielder, perhaps converting it directly into mana/hit points? ]</i></font><br><br>There is already a bard song that has a damage shield that absorbs magical damage. There's also a cleric "reverse damage shield" that heals anyone that hits the target. That's the extent of what we have, and nothing new along these lines are planned. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 11. Are there any plans to introduce a spell or item that REFLECTS spells back at the caster? ]</i></font><br><br>No. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 12. Why can't the monk-only weapons that look like gloves be worn on the hands, and add directly to the ATTACK stat instead of requiring them to be 1h blunt? ]</i></font><br><br>Items cannot be set to use hand-to-hand skill, and combat can't go to an "equipment" slot to get combat statistics. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 13. If Verant doesn't like "spoiler sites", then why are there no spell descriptions anywhere in the game? ]</i></font><br><br>I think that you've answered your own question. We don't like spoilers. We'd prefer people figure these things out on their own and maintain their own knowledge-base. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 14. Will players ever be able to construct golems? (A.k.a. summon a temporary "golem-type" pet through some complicated quest) ]</i></font><br><br>We could certainly, by use of trade skill or quest, award an item that summoned a pet of any particular type, however we have no plans to do that at present. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 15. Necros can charm the undead; enchanters can charm...well...everything. Will Magicians ever have the ability/spell to charm elementals or other summoned creatures? ]</i></font><br><br>No, we have no plans along these lines at present. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 16. Are there any plans for an expansion geared toward the 10 - 30 range of player rather than the higher levels? ]</i></font><br><br>Velious is geared towards a higher level-range, however Kunark has support for all level ranges. <br><br>With Velious, the thinking is that there is already plenty of content to support the continually migrating portion of the customer-base that is in the 10-30 range. <br><br>I'm unable to talk about any post-Velious plans at this time. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 17. The Trackers' Water Extractor - This is currently broken, is it not? The purification tablets do not seem to exist, and the NPC that mentions them won't respond. ]</i></font><br><br>I inquired about this time time back, when Kunark first launched, and it was verified at the time that the tablets do exist. If I need to check into it further, please let me know. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 18. Bandages vs. Aloe Swatches vs. Maneater Plant Salve vs. Tailored Silk Bandages: Is there any difference other than price i.e. More healing, faster healing, etc. ]</i></font><br><br>No difference at this time. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 19. Are there any plans to give clerics any type of special ability that is tied to whatever deity they worship? ]</i></font><br><br>No, there are currently no plans along these lines. However, there are plans and implemented pieces of deity-specific quests that return deity-specific rewards. <br><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: 20. Are there any races and/or classes that you, personally, would like to see added to the game? ]</i></font><br><br>If we added a warrior/wizard hybrid, could we call him a "fire fighter"?<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008814.html"><b>Mez and Bind Wound</b></a><br>I'd agree that being able to bind wounds while mesmerized is a bug. However can someone really bind wounds that much through the duration of the mez to make it much of a big deal? Do the posters feel that this is worth "correcting"? If we do correct it, it won't be on just the PvP servers, but across all of them.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008803.html"><b>Customer Dis-Satisfaction Reduction</b></a><br>Interesting idea. I don't see any issues that would prevent us from putting something like this in. I'll chat with the team about it and see what they think. And for future reference, can we speak of "increasing customer satisfaction" rather than "reducing customer dis-satisfaction" in the future?<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008661.html"><b>Bug on Tallon Zek?</b></a><br>I'd have to go with Brega on this one. Personally, whether I lose the cash to another player or destroy it right before death is inconsequential. Giving it some thought, I'd rather they loot it, because I then have a chance to come back and kill them before they have a chance to bank it. <br><br>I don't think that it's enough of an issue to pursue further at this point. Perhaps if others are of the same feelings as the original poster, we can give it some more thought.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008296.html"><b>Guild Accounts at Banks?</b></a><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: Because it would take work.]</i></font> <br><br>Every change takes work, it's just a question of how much work and whether or not the benefits of the change are worth diverting the manpower from other things that they could be working on, and whether the suggested changes are consistant with the game world. <br><br>I think that the suggestion does meet the "consistant with the game world" qualification, but am not sure that it would apply well to the others. Guilds do not currently exist as an entity, but rather as an entry within each character file. In order to implement this, guilds would have to be converted to be an entity all their own. Secondly, restrictions for nodrop and lore items would have to be implemented in ways that would only apply to guild banks. <br><br>It's not just work, but a substantial amount of manpower that's probably better served elsewhere at present. We won't rule it out completely though.<br><br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008528.html"><b>Cleric Issue</b></a><br>Though we just gained the ability to restrict items by deity, and could do the same with spells, we really don't have any plans to pursue this idea at present. There's enough issues with class and race balance, without having to likewise balance spells for deities within existing race/class combos.<br><br><LI><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008653.html"><b>Verant Ruined My Life!</b></a><br><font color=#072876><i>[Quote from original post: OK I am an EQ addict. If I do not play EQ for 16+ hours a day I go mad.<br><br>Wellll. One day I log on and I am missing ALOT of my characters. I relog, they are still gone. Now I panic and petition.<br>After 3-4 hours a guide tells me to contact a GM. After 3 hours the GM comes on and tells me he'll try to get my character back. 2 days later the GM denys they existed and ignores me. OK I just lost of year of my life here! I contact other GMs, I contact higher people in verant. And NO ONE in the whole company will help me it seems.<br><br>I have been playing since beta 3. My account has been active since day 1 of retail. Verant has ruined a year of my life.]</i></font><br><br>Fluffy, <br><br>I'm not sure what's going on in your case, but I've forwarded the thread to the management team in CS. <br>--<br>Secondly, I understand that you are upset about the issue, and I hope that we'll be able to rectify the problem, but I'll have to ask that you stop going around to other threads enaging in flameplay and name-calling.</UL>
